TITLE: Comparing Old Reason and New ReScript Syntax
DESCRIPTION: Examples of syntax differences between old Reason and new ReScript, including type arguments, string interpolation, polymorphic variants, arrays, lists, exceptions, and more.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rescript-lang/rescript-lang.org.git/blob/master/pages/docs/manual/v8.0.0/migrate-from-bucklescript-reason.mdx#2025-04-18_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: ReScript
CODE:
```
// Type arguments
option<int> // New ReScript
option(int) // Old Reason

// String interpolation
j`hello ${name}` // New ReScript
{j|hello ${name}|j} // Old Reason

// Polymorphic variants
#red // New ReScript
`red // Old Reason

// Arrays
[1,2,3] // New ReScript
[|1,2,3|] // Old Reason

// Lists
list{1, 2, 3} // New ReScript
[1,2,3] // Old Reason

// Exceptions
try compute() catch { | Not_found => Js.log("oops")} // New ReScript
try (compute()) { | Not_found => Js.log("oops")} // Old Reason

// First class module
module(S: Student) // New ReScript
(module S: Student) // Old Reason

// Object access
settings["visible"] = true // New ReScript
settings##visible #= true // Old Reason

// Object type
{"age": int} // New ReScript
Js.t({"age": int}) // Old Reason

// Attributes
@bs.deriving(accessors) // New ReScript
[@bs.deriving accessors] // Old Reason

// Recursive type declaration
type rec myList<'a> = Nil | Cons('a, myList<'a>) // New ReScript

// Using reserved keywords as identifiers
let "try" = true // New ReScript
```

